<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="445" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="14" pageNumber="445">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,835,861]" pageId="14" pageNumber="445">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin adjective “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peng et Chen" authorityYear="2022" box="[990,1107,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Axinoscymnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamulatus">
<emphasis box="[990,1107,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="445">hamulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, referring to its penis guide distinctly curved inwardly in lateral view.
</paragraph>
